Exercise 8

(a)

mod1 <- lm(mpg ~ horsepower, data = Auto)
summary(mod1)

Call:
lm(formula = mpg ~ horsepower, data = Auto)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-13.5710  -3.2592  -0.3435   2.7630  16.9240 

Coefficients:
             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) 39.935861   0.717499   55.66   <2e-16 ***
horsepower  -0.157845   0.006446  -24.49   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

Residual standard error: 4.906 on 390 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.6059,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.6049 
F-statistic: 599.7 on 1 and 390 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

(i)

Yes. The F-statistic is much greater than one, and the p-value is close to zero, so we can reject the null hypothesis that the regression coefficients are zero.

(ii)

The R-squared value is 0.61, so approximately 61% of the variance in mpg is explained by horsepower.

(iii)

The regression coefficient for horsepower is negative, so the relationship between horsepower and mpg is negative.

(iv)

Calculate the predicted mpg associated with a horsepower of 98:

predict(mod1, data.frame(horsepower = 98))
       1 
24.46708

Calculate the associated 95% confidence intervals:

predict(mod1, data.frame(horsepower = 98), interval="confidence")
       fit      lwr      upr
1 24.46708 23.97308 24.96108

Calculate the associated 95% prediction intervals:

predict(mod1, data.frame(horsepower = 98), interval="prediction")
       fit     lwr      upr
1 24.46708 14.8094 34.12476

(c)

Parts of this section are adapted from: https://data.library.virginia.edu/diagnostic-plots/ which has a nice explanation of residuals plots.)

#plot_lm_diagnostics(mod1) # There are issues with these plots, use base R instead
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(mod1)

Residuals vs Fitted Value

#lindia::gg_resfitted(mod1)
plot(mod1, which = 1)

The above plot can be inspected for trends in the residuals. There is a strong indication of non-linearity in the data. Additionally there appears to be more spread in the residuals on the right-hand side of the plot. That is to say there appears to be more variance in the residuals for observations with higher fitted values.

The below residual plot is for a linear regression of mpg on horsepower and horsepower^2. There appears to be little pattern in the residuals, suggesting that the quadratic term improves the fit to the data:

plot(lm(mpg ~ horsepower + I(horsepower^2), data = Auto), which = 1)

(see Figure 3.9 in ISLR for the same plots and discussion)

Normal-QQ Plot

#lindia::gg_qqplot(mod1)
plot(mod1, which = 2)

A Normal Q-Q plot shows if residuals are normally distributed. As the residuals in the above plot follow a straight line we can say they look to be normally distributed.

Scale-Location Plot

#lindia::gg_scalelocation(mod1) # !NOTE: The axis labels are reversed in this below plot
plot(mod1, which = 3)

A scale-location plot can be inspected to see if residuals are spread equally along the ranges of predictors. A horizontal red line with equally (randomly) spread points indicates equal variance of the residuals (homoscedasticity). A non-horizontal trend line and non-random spreading of the residuals indicate non-constant variance (heteroscedasticity). In the above scale-location plot there is a U-shaped trend line, and there appears to be more spread in the residuals in the right-hand half of the plot (larger fitted values). Therefore we can say there appears to be some heteroscedasticity.

Residuals Vs Leverage

#lindia::gg_resleverage(mod1)
plot(mod1, which = 5)

A plot of residuals vs leverage can indicate observations which have excessively high leverage. Such observations are more influential in forming the linear regression model. Instead of inspecting the plot for patterns, we look for points in the upper-right and lower-right corners of the plot. These are observations with both a large residual and large leverage and hence will heavily influence the estimated regression line. In the above plot there are no points with substantially higher leverage than others, and all points have a low leverage value. Note that the red dashed line for Cooks distance isnt even visible on the graph indicating that all points fall within acceptable range.

Aside
See page 91 and Table 3.10 in ISLR for discussion on improving the above model with a quadratic fit. In the below summary of such a model we can see how the quadratic fit has an improved R-squared value of 0.688 compared to 0.606 for the linear fit, and the p-value for the quadratic term is highly significant.

(i)

Yes. The model has an F-statistic of 224.5 which is well above 1 and has a very low p-value. This indicates a relationship between the predictors and the response.

(ii)

The predictors weight, year, origin2 and origin3 all have very low p-values indicating a statistically significant relationship to the response. The displacement predictor also has a low p-value and hence a statistically significant relationship to the response. The predictors cylinders, horsepower and acceleration do not have a statistically significant relationship to the response.

(iii)

The coefficient for the year variable is 0.777. This means that, on average, when the other variables are held constant, an increase of one year (of production) corresponds to an increase of 0.777 of mpg. That is to say, newer cars tend to be more fuel efficient.

We can see a number of the interaction terms are significant, including the horsepower:year and displacement:weight terms from the previous models. Interestingly, the first order terms displacement, weight and origin2 and origin3 are no longer significant. Per the hierarchy principle (page 89), we should include main effects in the model if we find that their interaction terms are significant. Also, the first order horespower term is now significant, even though it wasnt in the first model. This model has an R-squared value of 0.8862 which is an improvement on the previous models. Further investigation of interaction terms would be required to obtain an optimal model.

(f)

The horsepower variable was statistically significant in the simple linear regression model in Exercise 8, but not in the multiple linear regression model in Exercise 9 part (c). A non-linear transformation of the variable may produce interesting results. From inspection of the plot it looks like horsepower and mpg have a non-linear relationship. The below plots show mpg plotted against horsepower and its log, square root, and quadratic transformations:

p1 <- ggplot(Auto, aes(horsepower, mpg)) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue, alpha = 0.7)

p2 <- ggplot(Auto, aes(log(horsepower), mpg)) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue, alpha = 0.7)

p3 <- ggplot(Auto, aes(sqrt(horsepower), mpg)) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue, alpha = 0.7)

p4 <- ggplot(Auto, aes(horsepower^2, mpg)) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue, alpha = 0.7)

p1 + p2 + p3 + p4

It seems that the log transformation gives the most linear looking plot. Now fit an updated model combining the statistically significant variables from the earlier model with the log-transformation of horsepower:

(b)

  • The coefficient for Price is -0.055, suggesting that, on average, Sales will decrease by 550 units (-0.055 * 1000) for a unit increase in Price. The p-value for this coefficient is near-zero, indicating statistically significant evidence of this relationship.

  • The coefficient for UrbanYes is -0.022, suggesting that, on average, a stores Sales will decrease by 220 units (-0.022 * 1000) if it is located in an urban area, as opposed to a rural area (holding all other predictors constant). The p-value for this coefficient is very high, meaning there is no statistically significant evidence for this association

  • The coefficient for USYes is 1.201, suggesting that, on average, a stores Sales will increase by 1,201 units (1.201 * 1000) if it is located in the US, as opposed to another country (holding all other predictors constant). The p-value for this coefficient is very low, indicating statistically significant evidence of this relationship.

(c)

Our model takes the form: \[Y=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X_{1}+\beta_{2}X_{2}+\beta_{3}X_{3}+\epsilon\] where \(X_{1}\) is the Price variable, and \(X_{2}\) and \(X_{3}\) are dummy variables, used to encode the Urban and US variables respectively: \[ x_{i2} =\begin{cases}1 & \text{if }i\text{th store is Urban}\\0 & \text{if }i\text{th store is Rural}\end{cases} \] \[ x_{i3} =\begin{cases}1 & \text{if }i\text{th store is in US}\\0 & \text{if }i\text{th store is non-US}\end{cases} \] We can use these dummy variables as predictors in the regression equation: \[ y_{i} = \beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x _{i1}+\beta_{2}x_{i2}+\beta_{3}x_{i3} +\epsilon_{i}=\begin{cases}\beta _{0}+\beta_{1}x_{i1}+\epsilon_{i} & \text{if }i\text{th store is Rural and Non-US}\\\beta _{0}+\beta_{1}x_{i1}+\beta_{2}+\epsilon_{i} & \text{if }i\text{th store is Urban and Non-US}\\\beta _{0}+\beta_{1}x_{i1}+\beta_{3}+\epsilon_{i} & \text{if }i\text{th store is Rural and in US}\\\beta _{0}+\beta_{1}x_{i1}+\beta_{2}+\beta_{3}+\epsilon_{i} & \text{if }i\text{th store is Urban and in US}\end{cases} \] Using the values from the model we have: \[ \hat{y} = -0.05*\texttt{price}+\begin{cases}13.04 & \texttt{UrbanYes}=0, \texttt{USYes}=0\\13.02 & \texttt{UrbanYes}=1, \texttt{USYes}=0\\14.24 & \texttt{UrbanYes}=0, \texttt{USYes}=1\\14.22 & \texttt{UrbanYes}=1, \texttt{USYes}=1\end{cases} \]

Calculations:

The variables Price and USYes have low p-values indicating a statistically significant relationship with the response. We can reject the null hypothesis that the \(\beta\)-coefficient for these predictors is zero.

(d)

For the regression of \(Y\) onto \(X\) without an intercept, the t-statistic for \(H_{0}:\beta=0\) takes the form \(\hat{\beta}/\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})\), where

\[\hat{\beta} ~=~ \frac{\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}}{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}, \hspace{2cm} (3.38)\] \[\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})=\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i}-x_{i}\hat{\beta})^2}{(n-1)\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}}.\]

Algebraic proof:

To prove
Show that \[t = \hat{\beta}/\text{SE}(\hat{\beta}) = \frac{(\sqrt{n-1})\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i'=1}^n(y_{i'})^2-\left(\sum_{i'=1}^nx_{i'}y_{i'}\right)^2}}\] Proof
(1)
Let \(A\) be equal to the square of the numerator of the expression for \(\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})\):

\[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i}-x_{i}\hat{\beta})^2\] Expand: \[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i}^2-2\hat{\beta}x_{i}y_{i}+\hat{\beta}^2x_{i}^2)\]

Substitute in the expression for \(\hat{\beta}_{1}\) (remember to update indexes of the nested sums): \[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i}^2-2\frac{\sum_{j=1}^nx_{j}y_{j}}{\sum_{j=1}^n(x_{j})^2}x_{i}y_{i}+\frac{\left(\sum_{j=1}^nx_{j}y_{j}\right)^2}{\left(\sum_{j=1}^n(x_{j})^2\right)^2}x_{i}^2)\]

Expand the sum and rearrange: \[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-2\frac{\sum_{j=1}^nx_{j}y_{j}}{\sum_{j=1}^n(x_{j})^2}\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}+\frac{\left(\sum_{j=1}^nx_{j}y_{j}\right)^2}{\left(\sum_{j=1}^n(x_{j})^2\right)^2}\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\] There are no nested sums, so indexes \(i\) and \(j\) are the same. Rewrite with index \(i\) and rearrange: \[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-2\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}+\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}\]

Cancel terms and simplify : \[A=\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}\] (2)
Rewrite \(\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})\)using the expression derived for \(A\): \[\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})=\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}} \bigg/ \sqrt{(n-1)\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}\]

(3)
\[t=\hat{\beta}/\text{SE}(\hat{\beta})\] \[t = \left(\frac{\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}}{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}\right) . \sqrt{(n-1)\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2} \bigg/ \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}}\] Rearrange: \[t = \frac{(\sqrt{n-1})\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}.\sqrt{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}}{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2} \bigg/ \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}}\] \[t = \frac{(\sqrt{n-1})\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}.\sqrt{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2}}{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2} \bigg/ \frac{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}}\]

\[t = \frac{(\sqrt{n-1})\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}.\sqrt{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2} . \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2}}{\sum_{i'=1}^n(x_{i'})^2 . \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}}\] \[t = \frac{(\sqrt{n-1})\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{i})^2\sum_{i=1}^n(y_{i})^2-\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right)^2}} \hspace{2cm} \square\]

Exercise 12

(a)

The coefficient estimate \(\hat{\beta}\) for the linear regression of \(Y\) onto \(X\) without an intercept (\(i\)th fitted value given by \(\hat{y}_{i}=x_{i}\hat{\beta}\)): \[\hat{\beta}=\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}y_{i}\right) \bigg/ \left(\sum_{i'=1}^nx_{i'}^2\right)\] The coefficient estimate \(\hat{\beta}\) for the linear regression of \(X\) onto \(Y\) without an intercept (\(i\)th fitted value given by \(\hat{x}_{i}=y_{i}\hat{\beta}\)): \[\hat{\beta}=\left(\sum_{i=1}^ny_{i}x_{i}\right) \bigg/ \left(\sum_{i'=1}^ny_{i'}^2\right)\]

Clearly the numerators are equal, so the coefficients are equal when the denominators are also equal: \[\sum_{i=1}^nx_{i}^2=\sum_{i=1}^ny_{i}^2.\]

(f)

The results do not contradict. Rather, they are a result of collinearity. We saw that x1 and x2 were highly correlated. Indeed, x2 is generated linearly from x1. Therefore we can linearly predict x1 from x2 (and vice-versa) with a substantial degree of accuracy. When both variables are combined in the same linear model, one of them loses explanatory power because the variance it explains is already being explained by the other variable. Accordingly, if considered individually, both variables lead to the rejection of the null hypothesis. But if considered together, one of the variables is no longer significant.

Adapted from ISLR (pg 99):
Collinearity refers to the situation in which two or more predictor variables are closely related to one another. The predictors x1 and x2are highly correlated with each other, and we say that they are collinear. The presence of collinearity can pose problems in the regression context, since it can be difficult to separate out the individual effects of collinear variables on the response. In other words, since x1 and x2 tend to increase or decrease together, it can be difficult to determine how each one separately is associated with the response, y.
[In calculating the coefficient values that yield the smallest RSSthat is, the least squares estimatesa small change in the data could cause the coefficient values to move anywhere along a large range.] This results in a great deal of uncertainty in the coefficient estimates.
Since collinearity reduces the accuracy of the estimates of the regression coefficients, it causes the standard error for \(\beta_{j}\) to grow. Recall that the t-statistic for each predictor is calculated by dividing \(\beta_{j}\) by its standard error. Consequently, collinearity results in a decline in the t-statistic. As a result, in the presence of collinearity, we may fail to reject \(H_{0}:\beta_{j}=0\). This means that the power of the hypothesis testthe probability of correctly detecting a non-zero coefficientis reduced by collinearity.
A simple way to detect collinearity is to look at the correlation matrix of the predictors. An element of this matrix that is large in absolute value indicates a pair of highly correlated variables, and therefore a collinearity problem in the data. Unfortunately, not all collinearity problems can be detected by inspection of the correlation matrix: it is possible for collinearity to exist between three or more variables even if no pair of variables has a particularly high correlation. We call this situation multicollinearity. Instead of inspecting the correlation matrix, a better way to assess multi-collinearity is to compute the variance inflation factor (VIF).

                           color = ISLR_brown) +
  labs(x = "Coefficient in simple regression model", y = "Coefficient in multiple regression model")

It is not surprising to see that the coefficients have changed in value and even sign in some cases. In a simple model the coefficient is the average change in the response from a unit change in the predictor without consideration of the other predictors. In the multiple model, the coefficient is the average change in the response from a unit change in the predictor while holding the other predictors fixed. Because of possible correlations and collinearities between predictors it is possible that the coefficients will have different values and even signs in different models.
